  * xharbour/source/vm/arrayshb.c
    * modified ArrayToStructure to respect that pointer maybe also
      in HB_IT_INTEGER on some platforms - I do not use this feature
      please fix me if I made sth wrong

  * xharbour/source/vm/classes.c
    ! fixed bug in __CLSGETHANDLEFROMNAME

  * xharbour/source/vm/dynsym.c
    ! fixed pDynSym initialization in hb_dynsymNew()

  * xharbour/source/vm/estack.c
    * modified to respect that HB_IT_LONG may be long long C type

  * xharbour/source/vm/extend.c
  * xharbour/source/vm/itemapi.c
    - removed HB_IT_LONGLONG
    + added casting for GCC in double to long conversion - it's necessary
      when the double value is not in long what can be caused by storing
      ULONG value inside double
    * changed DAY/MONTH/YEAR in date functions from LONG to INT
    + added(changed) hb_parnint()/hb_retnint()hb_retnintlen()/hb_stornint()
      hb_itemGetNInt()/hb_itemPutNInt() - they operates on HB_LONG but
      internally chose to optimum integer ITEM

  * xharbour/source/vm/fm.c
    + added support for HB_STRICT_ALIGNMENT and HB_ALLOC_ALIGNMENT
      macros - some platforms like based on SPARC processors need it
    * use HB_PUT_LONG()/HB_GET_LONG() macros instead of direct casting
      to avoid GPF on platforms where strict alignment is necessary

  * xharbour/source/vm/hash.c
    * modified to work with HB_LONG

  * xharbour/source/vm/hbi18n.c
    ! fixed bug with hb_fs*() operation on bad handle
      Gian you often use 'int' as handle type in hb_fs*() functions.
      It could cause troubles in some systems where handle is bitfiled,
      can be bigger then 'int' and can returnes negative values which
      are still proper handles - try to always use FHANDLE type and
      to detect error compare ( hFile == FS_ERROR ) instead of
      ( hFile < 0 )

  * xharbour/source/vm/hvm.c
    - removed HB_IT_LONGLONG
    + added support for 64bit integers
    * modified to work with HB_LONG
    ! fixed badly set (or not set at all) numeric ITEMs length in
      some places
    ! cleaned the bugs with negating integers - on most machines (like x86)
      the integers are not 0 symmetric - it means that x = -x does not work
      for {INT,LONG,LONGLONG}_MIN (hb_vmNegate, ABS())
    * use HB_PUT_PTR()/HB_GET_PTR(), HB_PUT_LONG()/HB_GET_LONG() macros
       instead of direct casting to avoid GPF on platforms where strict
       alignment is necessary
    ! modified to eliminate unnecessary HB_LONG<->double conversions to
      reduce the possibility of destroying 64bit values
    ! fixed possible GPF in hb_vmSelectWorkarea()
    ! fixed some RT errors to be Clipper compatible
    % some optimizations

  * xharbour/source/vm/macro.c
    + added support for 64bit integers

  * xharbour/source/vm/maindllp.c
    * changed DAY/MONTH/YEAR in date functions from LONG to INT

  * xharbour/tests/rddspeed.prg
    * removed additional CR at EOLs

  * xharbour/tests/skipeval.prg
    * small modification to make the results similar

  * xharbour/tests/bldtest/bldtest.c
    * modified to respect recent changes

  * xharbour/utils/hbtest/hbtest.prg
  * xharbour/utils/hbtest/rt_ccall.prg
  * xharbour/utils/hbtest/rt_misc.prg
  * xharbour/utils/hbtest/rt_str.prg
    * replaced __PLATFORM__Linux with __PLATFORM__UNIX
    * some set proper string length to force RT error for __ARCH64BIT__
    - removed HB_IT_LONGLONG and modified to work with HB_LONG

  * xharbour/utils/xbscript/xbs_harb.ch
  * xharbour/utils/xbscript/xbscript.prg
    * replaced __PLATFORM__Linux with __PLATFORM__UNIX
    * casting

    After such long time there is no way I'll describe all things.
    I only collect what I remember - for deeper information please
    ask me and/or look at the sources. Also in last month I was adding
    some of this modification in small peaces when I was working and
    committing to the CVS. I hope I haven't broken any vital functions
    but in fact for a quite long time this modifications was synced
    with other changes in CVS - at the beginning after each CVS update
    I was analyzing the modifications and made manual synchronization
    but later I simply left them as is and only fixed the conflicts so
    I'm not sure the final effect as I should.
    HBTEST shows much more errors now but this are not errors I
    introduced - just simply some fixes exploits bad hacks in HBTEST
    which were hiding some xHarbour bugs or Clipper incompatibilities.
    In a few days I plan to begin the work on RDD modifications I was
    talking about. I will be thankful if you can report any problems
    with this version to this time.

